But would you say that it's
necessarily problematic

00:42:30.320 --> 00:42:31.670
that we can't do that?

00:42:31.670 --> 00:42:33.320
Because it means
that some people

00:42:33.320 --> 00:42:36.770
have a much harder time in
that socially important area.

00:42:36.770 --> 00:42:38.800
Like, should we be
able to tolerate

00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:39.800
that in a job interview?

00:42:39.800 --> 00:42:41.051
Or is that also not the point?

00:42:41.051 --> 00:42:42.925
JOHN MCWHORTER: There
should be no such thing

00:42:42.925 --> 00:42:43.820
as standard English.

00:42:43.820 --> 00:42:45.410
It's an abomination.

00:42:45.410 --> 00:42:46.565
We're stuck with it.

00:42:46.565 --> 00:42:48.560
That's just the way
it's going to be.

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:49.880
I'm a fatalist.

00:42:49.880 --> 00:42:52.820
But no, nobody would have any
trouble with comprehension

00:42:52.820 --> 00:42:55.155
in any real way if everybody
could just talk and write

00:42:55.155 --> 00:42:56.780
the way they wanted
to in this country.

00:42:56.780 --> 00:42:58.490
It wouldn't work in
Italy or Germany,

00:42:58.490 --> 00:43:01.040
where there's more
variation, but here, it's

00:43:01.040 --> 00:43:02.840
an arbitrary thing.

00:43:02.840 --> 00:43:05.050
So yes, I do think it's a shame.

00:43:05.050 --> 00:43:08.210
A person who doesn't feel
comfortable in standard English

00:43:08.210 --> 00:43:10.610
should be able to do an
interview the way they talk,

00:43:10.610 --> 00:43:12.812
because it would affect
comprehension not at all,

00:43:12.812 --> 00:43:15.020
and they'd be more articulate
talking the way they're

00:43:15.020 --> 00:43:16.340
used to talking.

00:43:16.340 --> 00:43:18.080
That day will never come.

00:43:18.080 --> 00:43:20.960
But yes, if I could
wave a magic wand.

00:43:20.960 --> 00:43:21.890
And really, it's true.

00:43:21.890 --> 00:43:24.000
When I think about
waving that magic wand,

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:25.250
there are always three things.

00:43:25.250 --> 00:43:27.350
And it's funny how it
changes throughout my life.

00:43:27.350 --> 00:43:31.610
One of them now-- my three are
nobody would ever be hungry.

00:43:31.610 --> 00:43:34.280
The idea that people are walking
around in the world sometimes

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:36.290
without enough to eat, that.

00:43:36.290 --> 00:43:40.310
Two, love would be based on the
inside rather than the outside.

00:43:40.310 --> 00:43:44.510
The idea that looks matter,
I think that's just horrible.

00:43:44.510 --> 00:43:47.300
Third, no standard
language, really.

00:43:47.300 --> 00:43:51.200
Everybody should just be able to
talk the way they want to talk,

00:43:51.200 --> 00:43:52.760
and everything would be fine.

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:54.860
But we're just stuck with
the reality on all three

00:43:54.860 --> 00:43:57.016
of those things.

00:43:57.016 --> 00:43:58.627
NATASHA AARONS: A
question of here.

00:43:58.627 --> 00:44:00.710
AUDIENCE: I'm hoping that
this isn't as open-ended

00:44:00.710 --> 00:44:02.510
as I think it is.

00:44:02.510 --> 00:44:05.960
A lot of what's changed in the
21st century versus the 20th

00:44:05.960 --> 00:44:07.640
is that we have
online communication.

00:44:07.640 --> 00:44:09.500
And specifically in
the last few years,

00:44:09.500 --> 00:44:12.620
you have phones and
keyboards coercing you

00:44:12.620 --> 00:44:15.497
towards standardized English.

00:44:15.497 --> 00:44:17.330
So for instance, I will
type in on my phone,

00:44:17.330 --> 00:44:19.070
and several of my
friends complain to me

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:22.289
about the ducking L
train this morning.

00:44:22.289 --> 00:44:22.830
And you can--

00:44:22.830 --> 00:44:25.516
JOHN MCWHORTER: I'm nodding
in complete ignorance.

00:44:25.516 --> 00:44:27.350
The ducking what?

00:44:27.350 --> 00:44:30.290
AUDIENCE: They wanted to type
a different word, but they've--

00:44:30.290 --> 00:44:30.955
JOHN MCWHORTER: Oh, got it.

00:44:30.955 --> 00:44:31.455
OK.

00:44:34.890 --> 00:44:36.160
Continue, sorry.

00:44:36.160 --> 00:44:38.404
AUDIENCE: And so this
happens on a spell check,

00:44:38.404 --> 00:44:40.070
and this happens on
a grammatical sense.

00:44:40.070 --> 00:44:42.230
And it happens a lot
in a coercive way

00:44:42.230 --> 00:44:44.690
towards a standard
very polite English,

00:44:44.690 --> 00:44:46.550
because a lot of
companies say, oh, we

00:44:46.550 --> 00:44:48.890
shouldn't AutoCorrect
towards another word,

00:44:48.890 --> 00:44:50.660
because that's a naughty word.

00:44:50.660 --> 00:44:53.450
How do you feel that that will
change the way people speak?

00:44:53.450 --> 00:44:57.140
And how should we
change that, if at all?

00:44:57.140 --> 00:45:00.126
JOHN MCWHORTER: You are--

00:45:00.126 --> 00:45:01.740
I'll put it this way.

00:45:01.740 --> 00:45:03.500
There are two forms of language.

00:45:03.500 --> 00:45:07.070
There's speaking, and
then there's writing.

00:45:07.070 --> 00:45:10.160
And we write informally
today to an extent

00:45:10.160 --> 00:45:11.660
that we didn't before.

00:45:11.660 --> 00:45:14.160
But really, the two
things are very different.

00:45:14.160 --> 00:45:17.060
And so the truth is that
whatever AutoCorrect

00:45:17.060 --> 00:45:20.090
does or doesn't do has--

00:45:20.090 --> 00:45:21.680
I don't mean this
in a flippant way,

00:45:21.680 --> 00:45:25.610
but it has no significant
effect on the way people speak.

00:45:25.610 --> 00:45:31.520
And we speak a lot more,
most of us, than we write.

00:45:31.520 --> 00:45:35.420
However, in general,
people are spontaneously

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:38.624
bidialectal in writing,
as well as in speech.

00:45:38.624 --> 00:45:40.040
So they're going
to be things that

00:45:40.040 --> 00:45:45.050
go on on keyboards that really
in the grand scheme of things

00:45:45.050 --> 00:45:47.090
mean that you can choose
to be or force yourself

00:45:47.090 --> 00:45:49.490
to be informal or formal.

00:45:49.490 --> 00:45:51.830
The decisions that
people make in terms

00:45:51.830 --> 00:45:55.130
of how these things correct
or don't, they're interesting,

00:45:55.130 --> 00:45:56.630
but I don't think
that they're going

00:45:56.630 --> 00:45:59.410
to affect the basic
sense that, one, language

00:45:59.410 --> 00:46:01.910
is speech, and two,
even when we're writing,

00:46:01.910 --> 00:46:05.080
we'll always be able to
do it in different ways.

00:46:05.080 --> 00:46:08.280
So for example, the word
ducking, so to speak,

00:46:08.280 --> 00:46:10.970
it's not going
away no matter what

00:46:10.970 --> 00:46:13.940
some program tries to do,
especially because that's

00:46:13.940 --> 00:46:17.210
primarily a spoken word.

00:46:17.210 --> 00:46:20.470
So we'll see, but
I take your point.

00:46:20.470 --> 00:46:24.180
NATASHA AARONS: I think we
have one more question here.

00:46:24.180 --> 00:46:25.807
AUDIENCE: Hey, good to see you.

00:46:25.807 --> 00:46:28.140
JOHN MCWHORTER: Max is one
of my students from Columbia.

00:46:28.140 --> 00:46:29.040
Hi, Max.

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:30.030
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:46:30.030 --> 00:46:32.370
So with the
prevalence of American

00:46:32.370 --> 00:46:37.206
pop culture and music
worldwide and its influence,

00:46:37.206 --> 00:46:39.330
do you see any interesting
effects of Black English

00:46:39.330 --> 00:46:42.790
on other Englishes worldwide
or even other languages?

00:46:42.790 --> 00:46:44.610
JOHN MCWHORTER: I do,
because it's not only

00:46:44.610 --> 00:46:46.620
here in the United States.

00:46:46.620 --> 00:46:50.190
Because of the music, that
way of speaking English

00:46:50.190 --> 00:46:53.230
is having an effect in
other parts of the world,

00:46:53.230 --> 00:46:55.680
including among people who
have no sense of whatever

00:46:55.680 --> 00:46:57.360
the social parameters are.

00:46:57.360 --> 00:46:58.830
They just do it.

00:46:58.830 --> 00:47:02.820
And also use the language
of that place in a way that

00:47:02.820 --> 00:47:05.160
has a black effect.

00:47:05.160 --> 00:47:07.260
I've heard rap in Germany
where I was thinking,

00:47:07.260 --> 00:47:08.880
this is black German.

00:47:08.880 --> 00:47:10.620
And most of these
people have never

00:47:10.620 --> 00:47:13.530
met an American black
person in their lives.

00:47:13.530 --> 00:47:15.030
And it's ironic.

00:47:15.030 --> 00:47:17.520
Once I was in New Guinea.

00:47:17.520 --> 00:47:19.800
I spent a short
week in New Guinea,

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:22.210
and everything was
completely different.

00:47:22.210 --> 00:47:23.370
The food.

00:47:23.370 --> 00:47:25.830
Indonesian is nothing like
any language any of us

00:47:25.830 --> 00:47:27.450
have probably ever known.

00:47:27.450 --> 00:47:30.720
It was about 200
degrees the whole time.

00:47:30.720 --> 00:47:33.510
The whole sense of
where a bathroom is

00:47:33.510 --> 00:47:36.750
and what it's like, even
in formal situations,

00:47:36.750 --> 00:47:39.900
was something that one had to
learn as one went, so to speak.

00:47:39.900 --> 00:47:41.744
It was absolutely amazing.

00:47:41.744 --> 00:47:43.410
The one thing that
was the most familiar

00:47:43.410 --> 00:47:46.500
was that the boys, including
many of them who compared

00:47:46.500 --> 00:47:49.500
to Americans are much smaller.

00:47:49.500 --> 00:47:52.020
I was so tall in this place.

00:47:52.020 --> 00:47:56.220
The boys could rap in
English sounding exactly

00:47:56.220 --> 00:47:59.100
like Jay-Z, even when they
didn't really speak English.

00:47:59.100 --> 00:48:02.370
And they speak Indonesian, but
they could go right into it.

00:48:02.370 --> 00:48:04.080
That, or Usher.

00:48:04.080 --> 00:48:06.540
A lot of them could
just sing exactly

00:48:06.540 --> 00:48:09.280
like Usher, when I could barely
have a conversation with them

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:10.020
otherwise.

00:48:10.020 --> 00:48:11.970
That was something I
found very interesting

00:48:11.970 --> 00:48:13.660
in terms of music making.

00:48:13.660 --> 00:48:16.950
And so 10 minutes ago, somebody
in New Guinea making music,

00:48:16.950 --> 00:48:18.120
god knows what they did.

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:19.140
I don't know.

00:48:19.140 --> 00:48:22.590
Today, a young boy in New
Guinea who makes music

00:48:22.590 --> 00:48:26.130
gets up with gestures,
and movements, and a sense

00:48:26.130 --> 00:48:28.620
of accompaniment, and
a sense of attitude,

00:48:28.620 --> 00:48:30.960
and that word we've
been talking about,

00:48:30.960 --> 00:48:33.670
even if it's in some language
we've never heard of.

00:48:33.670 --> 00:48:36.420
That's absolutely
fascinating to me.

00:48:36.420 --> 00:48:37.610
It's everywhere.

00:48:37.610 --> 00:48:40.510
No one would have expected
this 20 minutes ago.

00:48:40.510 --> 00:48:44.200
And here we are in this minute.

00:48:44.200 --> 00:48:45.470
It's the answer.

00:48:45.470 --> 00:48:47.807
NATASHA AARONS: We have
a question from Jonathan.

00:48:47.807 --> 00:48:49.265
AUDIENCE: Thank
you, Dr. McWhorter,

00:48:49.265 --> 00:48:50.460
or Professor McWhorter.

00:48:50.460 --> 00:48:54.450
I really appreciate all the
expertise that you've provided.

00:48:54.450 --> 00:48:56.170
One question that
I have, though,

00:48:56.170 --> 00:48:58.740
is when we talk about
language, at least

00:48:58.740 --> 00:49:01.830
in the American context
and about Black English,

00:49:01.830 --> 00:49:04.020
there seems to be
no way to separate

00:49:04.020 --> 00:49:08.520
the etymology of the language
and the political nature

00:49:08.520 --> 00:49:11.430
in the way that it's received,
in the way it's treated.

00:49:11.430 --> 00:49:14.730
So when we talk about the
boring code switching papers

00:49:14.730 --> 00:49:16.560
and things like that,
it seems like part

00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:18.226
of that's connected
to the fact of there

00:49:18.226 --> 00:49:20.250
is a weight to the
type of switching

00:49:20.250 --> 00:49:24.180
that one particular part of
the community or the population

00:49:24.180 --> 00:49:28.450
has versus others and
a question of power.

00:49:28.450 --> 00:49:34.230
So when we talk about the
future of how Black English is

00:49:34.230 --> 00:49:37.890
accepted academically, accepted
culturally, and accepted just

00:49:37.890 --> 00:49:40.230
in general as a
language, how do you

00:49:40.230 --> 00:49:42.930
think we have to come to terms
with the political and power

00:49:42.930 --> 00:49:43.830
aspect?

00:49:43.830 --> 00:49:47.070
Because it seems that, at least
within the American context,

00:49:47.070 --> 00:49:49.920
it wasn't just by chance that
standard-- what we consider

00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:52.020
standard English became
standard English,

00:49:52.020 --> 00:49:55.650
but it was an act of
power, an act of politics.

00:49:55.650 --> 00:49:59.040
And the way that Black English
has traditionally been treated

00:49:59.040 --> 00:50:00.540
and code switching
has been treated

00:50:00.540 --> 00:50:03.815
has been also an act
of political power,

00:50:03.815 --> 00:50:05.190
political subjugation,
or the way

00:50:05.190 --> 00:50:07.140
that certain communities
have embraced it has

00:50:07.140 --> 00:50:09.250
been an counter-act of power.

00:50:09.250 --> 00:50:13.230
So how, as an academic, as
someone who researches this,

00:50:13.230 --> 00:50:16.800
how do you come to terms, and
how does the academic community

00:50:16.800 --> 00:50:20.220
come to terms with that idea
of not only understanding

00:50:20.220 --> 00:50:24.962
there is an aspect of language
that is organic and changing

00:50:24.962 --> 00:50:26.670
and things like that,
but also that there

00:50:26.670 --> 00:50:29.727
is a political and
power aspect as well?

00:50:29.727 --> 00:50:31.560
JOHN MCWHORTER: That's
a very good question.

00:50:31.560 --> 00:50:35.250
Most of the people who study
Black English-- and honestly,

00:50:35.250 --> 00:50:39.330
what I do in linguistics is such
that I've got a couple of toes

00:50:39.330 --> 00:50:41.675
in Black English study,
enough to write this,

00:50:41.675 --> 00:50:42.930
but it's not my main thing.

00:50:42.930 --> 00:50:45.540
So that community, I
know them, like them,

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:48.840
but that's not where I go
to five conferences a year.

00:50:48.840 --> 00:50:52.890
Most of that community would
feel that what we need to do

00:50:52.890 --> 00:50:55.320
is change those power
relations, that we need

00:50:55.320 --> 00:50:57.330
to change the way people think.

00:50:57.330 --> 00:50:59.940
And often, many of them
say that standard English

00:50:59.940 --> 00:51:02.430
is a gatekeeper language
and it's not fair

00:51:02.430 --> 00:51:05.970
that a black speaker should have
to learn that at all, which I

00:51:05.970 --> 00:51:08.340
think, intellectually, is true.

00:51:08.340 --> 00:51:11.880
So the idea is that we
need to change society.

00:51:11.880 --> 00:51:13.680
That is a respectable view.

00:51:13.680 --> 00:51:15.540
It is not my politics.

00:51:15.540 --> 00:51:17.220
I'm just not that idealistic.

00:51:17.220 --> 00:51:18.750
So they are leftists.

00:51:18.750 --> 00:51:20.350
God bless the leftists.

00:51:20.350 --> 00:51:22.680
I'm more liberal in this sense.

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:25.560
I just don't see
how society is going

00:51:25.560 --> 00:51:27.360
to change the way
a lot of them do,

00:51:27.360 --> 00:51:29.580
which puts me at odds
with some academics.

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:30.600
But I think this.

00:51:30.600 --> 00:51:33.780
This is what I think we can get.

00:51:33.780 --> 00:51:35.940
I don't think we're going
to change that there's

00:51:35.940 --> 00:51:37.500
a degree of inequality.

00:51:37.500 --> 00:51:41.490
I hope that in 100 years that
inequality is not so tracked

00:51:41.490 --> 00:51:44.160
to skin color, but I
don't imagine that there

00:51:44.160 --> 00:51:45.390
will be no inequality.

00:51:45.390 --> 00:51:49.200
What I think is feasible is to
teach succeeding generations

00:51:49.200 --> 00:51:51.030
of Americans--
seceding generations

00:51:51.030 --> 00:51:53.480
of-- no-- succeeding
generations of Americans

00:51:53.480 --> 00:52:00.304
that different forms of language
are different, but not worse.

00:52:00.304 --> 00:52:02.220
So of course, people are
going to keep saying,

00:52:02.220 --> 00:52:03.719
you can't use it
in a job interview.

00:52:03.719 --> 00:52:06.330
And somebody like me will say,
you have spoken a true thing.

00:52:06.330 --> 00:52:07.230
Yes.

00:52:07.230 --> 00:52:11.910
But the point is if one
can hear Black English

00:52:11.910 --> 00:52:15.390
and not hear junk, but can
just think, it's different,

00:52:15.390 --> 00:52:17.760
the way somebody in
Milan hears somebody

00:52:17.760 --> 00:52:20.080
speaking Milanese Italian
and thinks, it's different.

00:52:20.080 --> 00:52:21.390
It's not junk.

00:52:21.390 --> 00:52:24.720
That's as far as I
imagine it getting.

00:52:24.720 --> 00:52:28.950
Now, are people who are hearing
that still probably going

00:52:28.950 --> 00:52:31.410
to think of black people
as lesser human beings?

00:52:31.410 --> 00:52:33.540
That's going to
be a harder fight.

00:52:33.540 --> 00:52:37.890
My attempt to kind of pull a
few bricks out of that wall

00:52:37.890 --> 00:52:40.287
is to try to make it clear
to people who will listen.

00:52:40.287 --> 00:52:42.120
And I find that if you
put it the right way,

00:52:42.120 --> 00:52:43.800
a critical mass do.

00:52:43.800 --> 00:52:47.100
What you're hearing
as mistakes isn't.

00:52:47.100 --> 00:52:50.754
And I definitely try to pull
the racism out of that equation,

00:52:50.754 --> 00:52:52.420
because it makes
people feel threatened.

00:52:52.420 --> 00:52:53.490
Should it?

00:52:53.490 --> 00:52:54.540
Probably, yeah.

00:52:54.540 --> 00:52:57.690
But still, you want to
keep their minds open.

00:52:57.690 --> 00:52:59.130
So that's what I think.

00:52:59.130 --> 00:53:00.600
Again, that's not
representative.

00:53:00.600 --> 00:53:02.160
Many people who
study the dialect

00:53:02.160 --> 00:53:06.390
would have a more revolutionary
approach than I do.

00:53:06.390 --> 00:53:08.190
Maybe I'm a little
cynical, but I

00:53:08.190 --> 00:53:10.590
think that we need
to be able to hear

00:53:10.590 --> 00:53:12.660
all the nonstandard
speech, but especially

00:53:12.660 --> 00:53:17.430
Black English, as interesting,
rather than broken down.

00:53:17.430 --> 00:53:19.564
So that's my mission.

00:53:19.564 --> 00:53:20.730
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:53:20.730 --> 00:53:22.220
JOHN MCWHORTER: Sure.

00:53:22.220 --> 00:53:25.290
NATASHA AARONS: Well, we're
unfortunately out of time.

00:53:25.290 --> 00:53:27.915
But we just want to thank you
on behalf of everyone here.

00:53:27.915 --> 00:53:28.636
JOHN MCWHORTER: Thank
you all for coming.

00:53:28.636 --> 00:53:29.080
NATASHA AARONS:
Everyone here at Google.

00:53:29.080 --> 00:53:30.260
JOHN MCWHORTER: Thank you.

00:53:30.260 --> 00:53:31.370
NATASHA AARONS: This
has been awesome.

00:53:31.370 --> 00:53:33.300
Thanks for dropping some
knowledge up in here.

00:53:33.300 --> 00:53:34.424
JOHN MCWHORTER: Dropped it.

00:53:34.424 --> 00:53:36.450
